    "38 GPIOs (LQFP48 package) — large keyboard matrices",
    "Built-in DFU bootloader — no external programmer needed for firmware updates",
    "Extremely cheap — $1-2 per chip",
    "I2C, SPI, USART peripherals",
    "CAN bus support (unique among keyboard MCUs)",
    "Used in many commercial keyboards (Planck, Preonic, etc.)"
  ],
  "concerns": [
    "No Bluetooth — wired USB only",
    "Only 16KB RAM — tight for complex firmware features",
    "48 MHz is slow compared to RP2040 or STM32F4",
